ctionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: probably from a placename Sachenbach in southern Germany, the first part of which is from Old High German <i>saher</i> ‘reed grass’ or ‘swamp’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Helena","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Helen  , used also in Germany, the Netherlands, Scandinavia, and Eastern Europe."],"variants":[]},{"name":"vel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Colloquial pet form of   Derek  , with alteration of the exposed <i>-r</i> of the short form to <i>-l</i> (  compare  Hal   and   Tel  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Derek","meanings":["From a Low German or Dutch form of <i>Theodoric</i> (  see  Terry  ), introduced into Britain during the Middle Ages by Flemish weavers, although it was not much used until a sudden explosion of popularity in the mid 20th century."]}]},{"name":"Heila","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Arabic origin, now fairly common in the English-speaking world, having been used as a name for an oriental beauty both by  Byron , in The Giaour (  1813 ) and Don Juan (  1819–24 ), and by  Lord Lytton  for the heroine of his novel Leila (  1838 ). In Arabic it means ‘night’, apparently alluding to a dark complexion."],"variants":[{"name":"Laila","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Leila ."]},{"name":"Layla","meanings":["‘Wine’ or ‘intoxication’; name of the beloved of the poet  Qays ibn-al-Mulawwaḥ  (  d. 688 )."]},{"name":"Lila","meanings":["Simplified spelling of   Leila ."]},{"name":"Lela","meanings":["Of Arabic origin, now fairly common in the English-speaking world, having been used as a name for an oriental beauty both by  Byron , in The Giaour (  1813 ) and Don Juan (  1819–24 ), and by  Lord Lytton  for the heroine of his novel Leila (  1838 ). In Arabic it means ‘night’, apparently alluding to a dark complexion."]},{"name":"Leyla","meanings":["Of Arabic origin, now fairly common in the English-speaking world, having been used as a name for an oriental beauty both by  Byron , in The Giaour (  1813 ) and Don Juan (  1819–24 ), and by  Lord Lytton  for the heroine of his novel Leila (  1838 ). In Arabic it means ‘night’, apparently alluding to a dark complexion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Helena vel Heila von Sachsen was born about 1090, in Saxony, Germany. She married Duke Wartislaw Swietoborzyc of Pomerania I after 1114, in Szczecin District, Szczecin, Poland. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1148, in Pomerania, Prussia, Germany, at the age of 59."},"et":{"um 1090–1148":"umbes 1090–1148","1091–1135":"1091–1135","1107–1150":"1107–1150","1127–1187":"1127–1187","1130–1177":"1130–1177","1090–1148":"1090–1148","1091":"1091","1090":"1090","1187":"1187","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","um 1090":"umbes 1090","1107":"1107","1127":"1127","1148":"1148","1135":"1135","about 1127":"umbes 1127","um 1130":"umbes 1130","9 August 1135":"9. august 1135","1177":"1177","nach 1114":"pärast 1114","Sachsen, Preußen, Deutschland":"Sachsen, Saksamaa","Pommern, Preußen, Deutschland":"Pommern, Freistaat Preußen, Saksamaa","Danzig, Pomorskie, Polen":"Gdańsk, pomorskie, Poola","Gdańskie, Polen":"gdańskie, Poola","Szczecin,Szczecenskiego,Poland":"Powiat szczeciński, szczecińskie, Poola"},"fi":{"um 1090–1148":"noin 1090–1148","1091–1135":"1091–1135","1107–1150":"1107–1150","1127–1187":"1127–1187","1130–1177":"1130–1177","1090–1148":"1090–1148","1091":"1091","1090":"1090","1187":"1187","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","um 1090":"noin 1090","1107":"1107","1127":"1127","1148":"1148","1135":"1135","about 1127":"noin 1127","um 1130":"noin 1130","9 August 1135":"9. elokuuta 1135","1177":"1177","nach 1114":"1114 jälkeen","Sachsen, Preußen, Deutschland":"Sachsen, Saksa","Pommern, Preußen,